Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
timing_case_a...al_propagation(25.10)    timing_case_a...al_propagation(25.10)

Name
       timing_case_analysis_for_sequential_propagation

Syntax
       timing_case_analysis_for_sequential_propagation

       {false | true | case_only | constant_only}

       Default: false

       Controls  whether  constants, which propagated to the inputs of sequen-
       tial devices like registers or flip-flops, are propagated to the output
       pins of those devices. This global variable will also affect the propa-
       gation of constants through integrated clock gating (ICG) cells  -  de-
       pending   on   the   setting   of  the  related  global  variable  tim-
       ing_case_analysis_for_icg_propagation.  Refer to the documentation  for
       this global variable for more information on ICG handling.

       The  constants  can be present in the analysis due to several different
       reasons - broadly breaking down to netlist constants and case analysis.
       The netlist constants come from connections to tie-hi or tie-lo  cells,
       a  1'b0/1'b1  assignment in the netlist, or explicit power rail connec-
       tions. The constants derived from these sources are  considered  to  be
       immutable.  The  constants  due to case analysis come strictly from the
       set_case_analysis constraint and are considered to be temporary -  con-
       figuring  the  analysis  to align to a certain mode.  You may choose to
       handle constants from any source in a similar manner or  customize  the
       handling based on the constant type.

       If you choose to allow propagation of only a specific type of constant,
       the output pin's state function must resolve to a constant by only con-
       sidering  inputs  pins  with the required constant type. Otherwise, the
       constant will not be propagated. The propagation of  constants  to  the
       output  of  a sequential device may affect how the timing checks on re-
       lated input pins are analyzed.  If all the possible  transitions  on  a
       given  input  pin are unable to change the constant state of the output
       pin, the timing checks on the input pin will be disabled by default.

       Changing the state of this global variable will change where  constants
       are present in the analysis, typically resulting in sets of timing arcs
       and timing checks being enabled or disabled. As a result, a full timing
       update, including a

       fresh  delay  calculation,  will be initiated when this setting is tog-
       gled.

       Note:   The  setAnalysisMode  -sequentialConstProp  parameter  provides
       overlapping functionality with this global variable. Changing the state
       of -sequentialConstProp will also change the state of this global vari-
       able. You should refrain from using both controls at the same time.

       You can use one of the following options:

       false  Disables  sequential  propagation  from any constant source (de-
              fault setting).

       true   Allows sequential propagation from any constant source - netlist
              or constraint-based.

       constant_only
              Allows sequential propagation only for constants that are due to
              the propagation of netlist-based constants.

       case_only
              Allows sequential propagation only for constants that are due to
              the  propagation  of   constraint-based   constants   from   the
              set_case_analysis command.

       To set this global variable, use the set command.

